<% content_for :title, "Self-hosting" %>
<% content_for :meta_description, "Self-host Logister with the local quickstart, environment setup, and production checklist." %>
<% content_for :canonical_path, docs_self_hosting_path %>
<% content_for :og_type, "article" %>
<% content_for :json_ld, json_ld({
  "@context" => "https://schema.org",
  "@type" => "TechArticle",
  "name" => "Logister Self-hosting",
  "url" => absolute_url_for(docs_self_hosting_path),
  "description" => "Self-host Logister with the local quickstart, environment setup, and production checklist."
}) %>

<div class="docs-page">
  <section class="docs-hero docs-hero-compact">
    <div>
      <p class="hero-kicker">Documentation / Self-hosting</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Run Logister yourself.</h1>
      <p class="hero-copy">
        This page distills the self-hosting guidance from the README into a public docs flow for local setup,
        required environment variables, and production rollout.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="docs-shell docs-layout">
    <div class="docs-rail">
      <%= render "sidebar" %>
    </div>

    <article class="<%= docs_article_classes %>">
      <section class="docs-article-header not-prose">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Guide overview</p>
        <h2>Use this guide when you want to run the Logister app yourself.</h2>
        <p class="docs-lead">
          Logister is a Rails app with PostgreSQL for control-plane data, Redis for jobs and cache, and optional
          ClickHouse for higher-scale analytics querying.
        </p>
        <div class="docs-outline-grid">
          <section class="docs-outline-card">
            <h3 class="docs-outline-title">Before you start</h3>
            <ul class="docs-outline-list">
              <li>Provision PostgreSQL and Redis first.</li>
              <li>Keep your Rails credentials and environment secrets ready.</li>
              <li>Treat local boot and production rollout as separate steps.</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <aside class="docs-outline-card">
            <h3 class="docs-outline-title">After reading this guide, you will know:</h3>
            <ul class="docs-outline-list">
              <li>How to boot Logister locally.</li>
              <li>Which environment variables matter in production.</li>
              <li>What to verify before calling a deploy healthy.</li>
            </ul>
          </aside>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="prerequisites" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Prerequisites</p>
        <h2>What you need before booting the app.</h2>
        <ul class="docs-list">
          <li>Ruby <code>4.0.1</code></li>
          <li>PostgreSQL <code>&gt;= 14</code></li>
          <li>Redis <code>&gt;= 7</code></li>
          <li>Optional ClickHouse if you want a dedicated analytics store</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="local-quickstart" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Local quickstart</p>
        <h2>Start the app locally.</h2>
        <p>Use this path for your first local boot so you can verify the app, database, and asset pipeline together.</p>
        <h3>1. Clone and configure</h3>
        <%= docs_code_block([
          "git clone https://github.com/taimoorq/logister.git",
          "cd logister",
          "cp .env.sample .env",
          "bundle install"
        ].join("\n"), language: "language-bash", shell: true, aria_label: "Copy self-host setup commands") %>
        <h3>2. Prepare the database</h3>
        <%= docs_code_block([
          "bin/rails db:prepare",
        ].join("\n"), language: "language-bash", shell: true, aria_label: "Copy self-host database commands") %>
        <h3>3. Start the app</h3>
        <%= docs_code_block([
          "bin/dev"
        ].join("\n"), language: "language-bash", shell: true, aria_label: "Copy self-host boot commands") %>
        <div class="docs-note docs-note-tip not-prose">
          <strong>Tip</strong>
          <p><code>bin/dev</code> also watches Tailwind locally and attempts to ensure Redis is available.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="environment" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Environment</p>
        <h2>Provide the minimum production configuration.</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Variable</th>
              <th>Why it matters</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>RAILS_MASTER_KEY</code></td>
              <td>Decrypts Rails credentials</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>DATABASE_URL</code></td>
              <td>Connects the primary Rails database</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>REDIS_URL</code></td>
              <td>Powers Sidekiq and app caching</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>LOGISTER_ADMIN_EMAILS</code></td>
              <td>Bootstraps admin access</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section id="production-checklist" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Production checklist</p>
        <h2>Checklist before you go live.</h2>
        <ol class="docs-list docs-list-numbered">
          <li>Set required secrets and connection URLs.</li>
          <li>Configure outbound email if you need confirmation and system email delivery.</li>
          <li>Run migrations during deploy.</li>
          <li>Enable Sidekiq in production.</li>
          <li>Optionally enable ClickHouse, Turnstile, and analytics consent tooling.</li>
        </ol>
        <div class="docs-note docs-note-warn not-prose">
          <strong>Important</strong>
          <p>Keep secrets out of committed config files. Use your deployment provider’s secrets manager or environment configuration.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="verify-deploy" class="docs-section docs-section-anchor">
        <p class="docs-eyebrow">Verify deploy</p>
        <h2>Check the app before you start sending production traffic.</h2>
        <p>
          A healthy deployment is more than “the web process booted.” Confirm the web app, jobs, and key product
          surfaces are all reachable before wiring your apps to it.
        </p>
        <%= docs_output_block([
          "Web app responds successfully",
          "Background jobs can start",
          "Project creation works",
          "API key creation works",
          "A test event appears in the project inbox"
        ].join("\n"), label: "Deployment verification") %>
        <div class="docs-note docs-note-tip not-prose">
          <strong>Next step</strong>
          <p>After the app is healthy, continue with the integration guide for the first application you want to connect.</p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </article>
  </div>
</div>
